    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my culinary science exam and I'm a bit stuck on the Maillard reaction. Can you explain what's actually happening chemically when bread crusts brown, and what are the specific temperature ranges where this usually kicks in?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a complex chemical process involving the browning of food, primarily the reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars. When bread crusts brown, these two components react under heat to create hundreds of different flavor and color compounds. This browning reaction typically begins to become significant around 285°F to 300°F (140°C to 150°C), though the rate increases dramatically as the temperature rises. These reactions are what give roasted meats and toasted bread their characteristic, delicious aromas.",
