    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I also read something about how moisture levels affect it. Why does it seem like if the surface is too wet, the browning doesn't happen as well? Is it just because the temperature stays low, or is there more to the chemistry of it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Moisture levels are crucial because water is a heat sink, meaning it absorbs a lot of energy, which keeps the surface temperature of the food lower. If the surface is too wet, the available heat energy is used to evaporate the water rather than to drive the chemical reactions of the Maillard process. This delay in reaching the necessary high temperatures prevents the amino acids and sugars from reacting effectively. Think of it like trying to start a fire in a damp pile of kindling; the energy goes into just making the water vapor instead of igniting the fuel.",
