      "content": "While the reaction is a general principle, the specific types of sugars and amino acids can certainly influence the speed and flavor profile of the browning. Certain reducing sugars, like fructose, tend to participate more readily in the initial stages of the Maillard reaction than others. Similarly, the specific amino acid structure can dictate which volatile compounds are formed, leading to different flavor notes—some amino acids produce more savory, meaty notes, while others yield nuttier or sweeter smells. It's a symphony of molecules, where the components dictate the final composition.",
